# Provenance — the design-system catalog is upstream's, fetched not committed

The `design/systems/<brand>/` packages are taken **verbatim** from the open-source **Open Design**
project — the open Claude-Design alternative that ships brand-grade design systems on a fixed section
schema (visual theme, color, typography, components, layout, depth, do's/don'ts, responsive, agent
guide).

- Upstream:   https://github.com/nexu-io/open-design
- Path:       design-systems/<brand>/
- Commit:     f4fe5ad7579b81f9722f6db051d9768abc570577
- Catalog:    150 systems, each as its full curated agent package — `DESIGN.md`, `USAGE.md`,
              `tokens.css`, `design-tokens.json`, `components.html`, `components.manifest.json`,
              `manifest.json`, `tailwind-v4.css` (copied verbatim). We skip only `preview/` (HTML
              preview pages), `source/` (audit evidence), and the localized `DESIGN-*.md` translations.
- License:    Apache License 2.0 — see LICENSE.upstream (copied from upstream at the pinned commit)

**The heavy per-brand packages are NOT committed to this repo.** Only a safety-net subset is vendored
in git — the default-pool neutrals (`default`, `friendly`, `warm-editorial`) plus `stripe` — so a
blind `random` draw, the look-change baseline, and the tests all work offline with zero fetch. The
remaining ~146 systems are pulled at standup from the pinned commit above by `bin/fetch-design-catalog`
(bootstrap.sh runs it once), which is what lets an explicit `LILA_DESIGN=<brand>` pin reach any system.
INDEX.md, this PROVENANCE, and LICENSE.upstream stay tracked — they are lila's curation, not bulk.

We use upstream's curated `tokens.css` (the machine-readable token bindings agents paste verbatim) and
`components.html` reference markup DIRECTLY — lila does NOT re-derive tokens or hand-author a component
layer. The render simply copies these curated assets into the app; the agent adapts the reference
components to the stack's idiom per the system's own `USAGE.md`.

## What lila contributes (and what it does NOT)

lila does **not** author or alter these systems. We adopt Open Design's file format and its systems
wholesale. lila's contribution is the machinery *around* them: the tiered pools (default / browsable /
full, recorded in INDEX.md), the safe-by-default draw + lock, the once-only invitation, the per-stack
render into real tokens, and the verification. The catalog itself is upstream's.

The `DESIGN.md` files are copied unmodified. INDEX.md is generated by lila (the `pool` column is lila's
curation layer; everything else is lifted from each file's own H1 / `> Category:` / voice lines).

## Updating the catalog

This is a deliberate, reviewable bump — never an auto-sync. To refresh:

1. Update the `Commit:` line above to the new upstream commit, and refresh `LICENSE.upstream`.
2. Regenerate INDEX.md (re-run the vendoring step that produced it) and re-curate the `default` /
   `browsable` pools — never auto-promote a freshly-added system into a pool the framework draws from
   blindly.
3. Refresh the committed safety-net subset to the new commit:
   `FORCE=1 bin/fetch-design-catalog default friendly warm-editorial stripe`, then commit those dirs.
   Everything else is pulled at standup from the new pinned commit — nothing else to copy by hand.
